<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1407,1685]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,502,1551,1576]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[512,731,1551,1576]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scolecoides">
<emphasis box="[512,731,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia scolecoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to southern Brazilian 
<taxonomicName box="[1124,1242,1551,1576]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="10" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, restricted to the area between the Juruena and Xingu rivers (
<figureCitation box="[652,722,1588,1613]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[1088,1138,1588,1612]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Pará</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1195,1345,1588,1612]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scolecoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia scolecoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fossorial, and according to museum records it inhabits open vegetation enclaves. Despite its description more than 50 years ago, natural history information about 
<taxonomicName box="[935,1095,1660,1685]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scolecoides">
<emphasis box="[935,1095,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">B. scolecoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is still lacking.
</paragraph>
